          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Next Question Correctedness",
          "Correct (Green) vs Incorrect (Red)",
          "761 Biology students, 528 Law students, 383 Cardiff students, 382 Sydney19 learners and 198 Sydney23 learners ",
          "Biology, Law  & others",
          "Sequence of Answers, Question Text",
          "[Structural Embeddings from Positive and Negative answers to questions, MCQ Embeddings - GLoVe, Student Embeddings]",
          "Previous graph models struggle with 2 things: \n\n1. Establish a relationship between learners and questions.\n\n2. Dealing with noise associated with the randomness of learner content generation.\n\n",
          "The model creates augmented graphs for students and questions. These are subsequently passed through 2 encoders (a positive encoder and a negative encoder). This graph encoder is “compatible” with any GNN model.\n\nThe second innovation comes from the adopted contrastive objective  function - which aims to maximize similarity of nodes across different views. \n\nThe final innovation stems from the use of GPT to generate semantyc embeddings.",
          "Augmentation of the graphs is done using stochastic methods to create the positive and negative sub-graphs.\n\nAuthors use Graph Attention Networks as the model used for the creation of embeddings. Sequences are converted to knowledge components using the GPT 3.5 Turbo, which are converted to embeddings using GloVe.\n\nThe initialization of learner embeddings is random - since there is no student profile. \n\n\n",
          "Random, GCN, GAT, SGCN, SBGNN, SBCL, LLM-SBCL",
          "Holdout Method",
          "Biology\n{F1-Score: 0.787 - LMM-SBCLL}\n\nLaw\n{F1-Score: 0.908 - LMM-SBCLL}\n\nCardiff2012\n{F1-Score: 0.734- LMM-SBCLL}\n\nSydney19\n{F1-Score: 0.694 - LMM-SBCLL}\n\nSydney23\n{F1-Score: 0.76- LMM-SBCLL}",
          "Authors propose a novel graph model that includes a positive and a negative encoder for the sequences of the answers before feeding the embeddings to an MLP. \n\nAuthors also use an LLM to extract the knowledge concepts and use them as a feature for the models. \n\nAblation studies show that the model LLM-SBCL has every layer be relevant.",
          "- What are the average and standard deviation of F1-Score for in an implementation of the holdout method?\n\n- Small student population.\n\n- Limited capacity in cold-start scenarios\n\n- Does not consider interactions among students or questions\n\n- Does not explore any other LLMs"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 9
    }
  ],
